post_text:
The following are the protocols in play for Thursday's C/JV/V Volleyball matches at Bishop Neumann, starting at 5:00 pm.

COVID-19 Guidelines:
+Attendance Capacity is 50%.
+Self-screening and temperature checks before travel are required.
+Social distancing in the Neumann gym is required where possible.
+Masks are REQUIRED for all spectators in the Neumann gym.
+Players and coaches are required to wear masks on the bench.
+Players on the court are not required to wear masks, but it is encouraged.
+Volleyballs will be sanitized after each match.
+Post-game handshakes are currently suspended.
+When the final match is completed we ask that players, coaches and spectators leave the gym in a timely manner.
+No one is allowed on the court after the contests.
+Outside food/team meals are not allowed in the building.
+Showers will not be available after the contests.

+When the final match is completed we ask that players, coaches and spectators leave the gym in a timely manner.
+No one is allowed on the court after the contests.
+Outside food/team meals are not allowed in the building.
+Showers will not be available after the contests.

Good afternoon,
During any year, we are always rushing to get everything ready for the school year. That is more true than ever for this year! The attached letter explains the Hybrid Attendance Plan that has been developed for Mead Public Schools. Basically, PK-6 will attend school as they normally would. Grades 7-12 would move to remote learning but still attend one day per week according to the developed schedule. Grade 7's attendance plan will depend on the time of year, and is explained in the letter. As always, I hope this helps you plan for the school year!

PJ Quinn, Superintendent

post_text:
Please follow the link below for information about the plan for graduation on June 13th.

Based on the Directed Health Measures (DHM) that will begin on June 1, we plan to host graduation on Saturday, June 13. Baccalaureate is scheduled for 1:30, and Commencement will follow at 2:00. To meet the requirements of the DHM, each graduate will be limited to 15 guests who will be expected to sit together. More details for parents of graduating seniors are included in the attached letter. We are also planning to live stream the event and will provide more information at a later date. Please contact Mr. Quinn or Dr. Rawson with any questions

https://www.meadpublicschools.org/vimages/shared/vnews/stories/5e7126c455e63/Graduation%20Letter%205-26-20.pdf

post_text:
Guidance from the Governor and the Nebraska Schools Activities Association allows school weight rooms to open June 1.

Mead will open the weight room for student-athletes. Student-athletes have been organized into groups of 10, which we feel will allow for appropriate social distancing in the weight room. Other precautions will be in place as well.

Participants and their parents are required to sign and return a waiver to participate. The waiver and other information is available are attached.

We are waiting for the Dept. of Ed. to interpret the new guidelines and how they effect graduation.

post_text: Tomorrow Wednesday, April 15th at 8:20 P.M. (20:20 military time) Mead Public Schools will be participating in the "Be The Light" movement where schools across the nation are turning on their stadium lights for 20 minutes. In honor of Mead Raider Nation: students, athletes, staff and our 2020 seniors. We are thinking of you and miss you all! Feel free to drive through the parking lot but please remember to stay in your cars and not congregate. Show your support by turning the outside lights on at your home! #MeadRaiderNation #BeTheLight #BeaconOfLight

Some information for next school year from the NSAA concerning 2020-21 Sports Physicals:

The NSAA has waived the requirement for a new sports physical for students entering 8th, 10th, 11th and 12th grade in 2020-21, provided they already have a physical on file at the school from the 2019-20 school year.

Students entering 7th and 9th grade will still need to have physical dated on/after May 1, 2020 to participate in sports for the 2020-21 school year.

If you have any questions, please contact Terry Hickman at thickman@esu2.org or message this page.

post_text:
If you would like to be able to monitor your High School student's progress on Canvas, you can set yourself up as an "observer".

Before posting the instructions, a word of warning: there are many steps. If you have issues with following this process, please contact Dawn Moser at the High School.

So, if a parent/guardian wants to be added as an observer, their student needs to log in to Canvas. Once logged in,
1. click on "account"
2. click on "settings"
3. click on "pair with observer"
4. a code will be generated for you
5. copy code
6. log out of student account
7. on Canvas log in page, click on "need a Canvas account, click here, it's free"
8. click on "parents sign up here"
9. complete parent form and click on "start participating"

Abby Miller
March 24 at 1:34 PM ·

Happy National Ag Day!

In honor of today, here is the first of many ag literacy activity videos I will be sharing. Given the current status of MPS, I’m sure there are some bored kiddos at home. These videos will include hands on activities, experiments, books and so much more!

Today’s topic introduces us to the importance of agriculture.

Materials:
-play dough and plastic knife

OR

-paper, drawing materials, and a circular object to trace (or can print and color the diagram attached below)

Enjoy, keep busy, and stay healthy!

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1P6dmFTq1RxfEXHxpaXI6_oQ9z_sPBH70/view?usp=sharing

post_text: Third grade created pet rocks last Thursday in library skills after reading Charlotte and the Rock by Stephen W. Martin. This book is one of the Golden Sower pictures book nominees from the Nebraska State Award list for 2019-2020. The pet rocks they designed in response to the story were so creative! Their “crazy face” picture was so funny I had to share that as well. What a creative group of students!

post_text:
Preschool Registration
Children who are 3 years old by July 31, 2020 are eligible to attend morning preschool for the 2020-2021 school year.

Children who are 4 years old by July 31, 2020 are eligible to attend afternoon preschool for the 2020-2021 school year.

You will need to provide the following items before school starts:

*Official Birth Certificate
*Mead Public Schools Student Enrollment Form
*Immunization Records

To start the registration process, call the elementary school at 402-624-6465 and ask for Shelly or Jessica. A preschool information letter will be sent to all registered students at the beginning of summer.

To find out more about the preschool program, join us at our Preschool Advisory Committee Meeting on April 20, 2020 at 6:30 PM.

post_text:
The Mead Academic Decathlon team competed at state this Friday and Saturday. More details to come, but a quick rundown:

The Super Quiz team placed 4th in the Small School division.
Jackson Munter (Varsity) medalled in Essay (2nd), Literature (3rd) and Science (3rd).
Cali Carritt (Scholastic) earned a 2nd place medal in Interview.
Mystic Hartgrave (Varsity) earned a 2nd place medal in Mathematics.
Emily Hanson was Mead's Top Overall Scorer.

All the students competed well and worked towards a very successful experience at state.
